## Routing Mapping

### Laravel Routes → Next.js App Router

| Laravel Route | Next.js App Router Path |
|---------------|------------------------|
| `GET /products` | `app/products/page.tsx` |
| `GET /products/{id}` | `app/products/[id]/page.tsx` |
| `GET /products/create` | `app/products/create/page.tsx` |
| `GET /products/{id}/edit` | `app/products/[id]/edit/page.tsx` |
| `GET /profile` | `app/profile/page.tsx` |
| `GET /dashboard` | `app/dashboard/page.tsx` |

### Route Params

In Next.js 15, `params` is now a **Promise** and must be awaited:

```tsx
// app/products/[id]/page.tsx
export default async function ProductDetail({ params }: { params: Promise<{ id: string }> }) {
    const { id } = await params;
    return <ProductDetailClient id={parseInt(id)} />;
}

// Client component that uses TanStack Query
'use client';
function ProductDetailClient({ id }: { id: number }) {
    const { data: product } = useProduct(id);
    return <h1>{product?.name}</h1>;
}
```

> **Next.js 15 breaking change**: `params`, `searchParams`, `headers`, `cookies`, and `draftMode` are all async now. If you access them synchronously, it still works in development but will warn — and will break in production builds.

### Navigation

```tsx
import Link from 'next/link';
import { useRouter } from 'next/navigation';

// Link
<Link href="/products">Products</Link>
<Link href={`/products/${id}`}>View</Link>

// Programmatic
const router = useRouter();
router.push('/products');
router.replace('/login'); // no history entry
```

