## Server Components vs Client Components

| Use Case | Component Type |
|----------|---------------|
| Fetching data at build/request time (no interactivity) | Server Component (default) |
| Form with state, event handlers, `useQuery` | Client Component (`'use client'`) |
| Static layout, navigation | Server Component |
| Anything with `useState`, `useEffect`, TanStack Query | Client Component |

```tsx
// Server Component — can fetch directly (no TanStack Query needed)
// app/products/page.tsx (server component, no 'use client')
async function getProducts() {
    // Next.js 15: fetch is NOT cached by default (changed from v14)
    // Add revalidate or cache option explicitly when you want caching
    const res = await fetch(`${process.env.API_URL}/api/products`, {
        next: { revalidate: 60 },
    });
    return res.json();
}

export default async function ProductsPage() {
    const { data: products } = await getProducts();
    return <ul>{products.map(p => <li key={p.id}>{p.name}</li>)}</ul>;
}
```

> Use **Server Components** for initial page data when possible — they're faster (no client JS). Use **Client Components** + TanStack Query for interactive, frequently-updating data.

